# Theme colors

## Source of truth

- **All theme color values** are defined under `Mobile/constants/colors/` inside a folder named `*Theme` (e.g. `lightTheme/`, `darkTheme/`).
- **`ThemeColors` is the contract**: `Mobile/constants/colors/types.ts` (and its subtypes) define the required shape for every theme object. Theme definitions must fully obey those types.
- **No circular imports**: avoid require cycles across theme files/modules. When in doubt, **copy the hex/rgba value** into each theme definition instead of importing a shared constant.

## Using colors in components

- Components must **not** hard-code color values in stylesheets or constants.
- Components should read colors from the theme via `useColorTheme()` (ColorThemeContext).
- Small exceptions are allowed only for **computed/derived colors** (e.g. minimap segment halo colors computed from theme inputs).

### ✅ GOOD (component uses theme colors)

```tsx
import { useColorTheme } from "@/context/theme/ColorThemeContext";
import { Text, View } from "react-native";

export function Example() {
  const themeColors = useColorTheme();
  return (
    <View style={{ backgroundColor: themeColors.card.background }}>
      <Text style={{ color: themeColors.text.primary }}>Hello</Text>
    </View>
  );
}
```

### ❌ BAD (hard-coded colors in component)

```tsx
import { Text, View } from "react-native";

export function Example() {
  return (
    <View style={{ backgroundColor: "#ffffff" }}>
      <Text style={{ color: "#111827" }}>Hello</Text>
    </View>
  );
}
```

## Prefer existing theme tokens

When building a new screen or component, **reuse existing semantic colors** (`text`, `card`, `separator`, `button`, `preview`, etc.) before adding a new key to `ThemeColors`.

- Add a **component-specific** theme subtree (e.g. `themeColors.pageScreen.text`) only when the color is **shared across multiple instances** of that prototype family, or when it encodes **semantics that do not fit** any existing token.
- One-off layout colors for a single screen should still use shared tokens, not a new named slot.

### ✅ GOOD (new page screen uses shared `text` tokens)

```tsx
import { useColorTheme } from "@/context/theme/ColorThemeContext";
import { Text, View } from "react-native";

export function NewPageScreen() {
  const { text, card } = useColorTheme();
  return (
    <View style={{ flex: 1, backgroundColor: card.background }}>
      <Text style={{ color: text.primary }}>Title</Text>
      <Text style={{ color: text.secondary }}>Subtitle</Text>
      <Text style={{ color: text.error }}>Error message</Text>
    </View>
  );
}
```

### ❌ BAD (new page screen adds a dedicated theme subtree)

```tsx
// types.ts — avoid unless this color is reused by a prototype family
// pageScreen: { title: string; subtitle: string; error: string }

export function NewPageScreen() {
  const { pageScreen } = useColorTheme();
  return (
    <View>
      <Text style={{ color: pageScreen.title }}>Title</Text>
      <Text style={{ color: pageScreen.subtitle }}>Subtitle</Text>
    </View>
  );
}
```

## Mapped component colors: use key constants

For families of similar components with a shared prototype (e.g. **Buttons**, **Badges**), define **key constants** that are used to map a key to its theme colors:

- Use constants like `Mobile/constants/buttons.ts` or `Mobile/constants/badges.ts`.
- Use the key to select a color entry under the appropriate theme subtree (e.g. `themeColors.button.standard[KEY]`).
- **Exception**: if a component is already mapped to a shared enum in another package (e.g. difficulty badges keyed by `ACADifficultyRatings` from `ropegeo-common`), use that enum as the key instead of creating a new constant key.

### ✅ GOOD (component picks a theme entry by key)

```tsx
import { useColorTheme } from "@/context/theme/ColorThemeContext";
import { SOME_BUTTON_KEY } from "@/constants/buttons";
import { Pressable, Text } from "react-native";

export function ExampleButton() {
  const themeColors = useColorTheme();
  const colors = themeColors.button.standard[SOME_BUTTON_KEY];
  return (
    <Pressable style={{ backgroundColor: colors.backgroundColor }}>
      <Text style={{ color: colors.textColor }}>Tap</Text>
    </Pressable>
  );
}
```

### ❌ BAD (prototype component hard-codes its colors)

```tsx
import { Pressable, Text } from "react-native";

export function ExampleButton() {
  return (
    <Pressable style={{ backgroundColor: "#2563eb" }}>
      <Text style={{ color: "#ffffff" }}>Tap</Text>
    </Pressable>
  );
}
```

## Defining new theme colors

- **First** check whether an existing token already matches (especially `text`, `card`, `separator`, `image`, `button`).
- Add/extend types in `Mobile/constants/colors/types.ts` only when a new semantic or prototype-mapped slot is justified.
- Add the new color values to **every** theme folder under `Mobile/constants/colors/*Theme/` and ensure they satisfy the types.
- Prefer repeating literals over importing between theme modules to avoid cycles (re-exporting an unchanged subtree such as badges from an existing theme is acceptable when the palette is intentionally identical).

## Adding a new named theme (Settings + runtime)

When introducing a palette beyond Light/Dark (e.g. **Fabulous**), update these touchpoints:

1. **Theme definition** — Create `Mobile/constants/colors/<name>Theme/` with a root `index.ts` exporting a `ThemeColors` object (mirror `lightTheme/` / `darkTheme/` structure: `buttons/`, `badges/`, etc.).
2. **Palette registry** — Register in `Mobile/constants/colors/index.ts`:
   - Extend `ThemePaletteKey` with the new key (PascalCase, e.g. `"Fabulous"`).
   - Add the theme to `COLORS`.
3. **Settings enum** — In `Mobile/constants/settings/types.ts`:
   - Add the preference to `ThemePreference` (PascalCase string literal).
   - Append it to `THEME_PREFERENCES` (order controls Settings chip order).
   - `Settings.parseTheme` validates against `THEME_PREFERENCES` automatically.
4. **Runtime resolution** — In `Mobile/context/ColorThemeContext.tsx`:
   - Map the new preference to its `COLORS` key in `resolveThemePaletteKey`.
   - Set `resolveColorTheme` to `"light"` or `"dark"` for system chrome (status bar, etc.); use `"dark"` for deep backgrounds, `"light"` for light backgrounds.
5. **Settings UI** — In `Mobile/components/screens/settings/ThemeSettingsSection.tsx`:
   - Add a label in `THEME_LABELS`.
   - Add swatch colors in `swatchColors` (`primary` = `background`, `secondary` = accent such as `text.link`).

`Auto` is not a palette: it follows the system scheme and picks `COLORS.Light` or `COLORS.Dark`.
